C.2.2 In energy systems, modelled global pathways (considered in the literature) limiting global warming to 1.5Â°C with no or
limited overshoot (for more details see Figure SPM.3b) generally meet energy service demand with lower energy use,
including through enhanced energy efficiency, and show faster electrification of energy end use compared to 2Â°C (
high
confidence
). In 1.5Â°C pathways with no or limited overshoot, low-emission energy sources are projected to have a higher
share, compared with 2Â°C pathways, particularly before 2050 (
high confidence
). In 1.5Â°C pathways with no or limited
overshoot, renewables are projected to supply 70â85% (interquartile range) of electricity in 2050 (
high confidence
). In
electricity generation, shares of nuclear and fossil fuels with carbon dioxide capture and storage (CCS) are modelled to
increase in most 1.5Â°C pathways with no or limited overshoot. In modelled 1.5Â°C pathways with limited or no overshoot,
the use of CCS would allow the electricity generation share of gas to be approximately 8% (3â11% interquartile range)
of global electricity in 2050, while the use of coal shows a steep reduction in all pathways and would be reduced to close
